<p>
  the "free upgrade" is one of the most successful marketing frames in british telecoms. it suggests generosity — the provider is giving you something better, for nothing. in practice, it's a contract renewal dressed as a gift.
</p>

<h3>how the upgrade cycle works</h3>

<p>
  you're 18 months into a 24-month contract on a handset + airtime deal. you're paying £45/month. the provider calls or emails: "congratulations — you're eligible for an early upgrade to the latest model, at no extra cost." you say yes. what just happened?
</p>

<p>
  your old contract was cancelled. a new 24-month contract started — with a new handset cost amortised into the monthly fee. your £45/month has become a new £45/month, but you've just signed up for 24 more months. the "free" part is that there's no upfront payment. the cost is the lock-in.
</p>

<h3>the sim-only option people ignore</h3>

<p>
  once your handset is paid off — typically after 24 months — your monthly bill should drop by £15–25/month. this is the handset repayment portion. if you keep the phone and switch to sim-only, you're paying £10–20/month instead of £45.
</p>

<p>
  but most people don't do this. they see the "free upgrade" offer and take it, locking in another 24 months at the full rate. the difference over 2 years: £600–900 you didn't need to spend, for a phone that's marginally better than the one you already had.
</p>

<h3>what perch. recommends</h3>

<p>
  when your contract ends, check your phone. if the screen isn't cracked and the battery lasts a day, cancel the handset portion, go sim-only, and bank the difference. if you really want a new phone, buy it outright — £500–800 upfront saves you the £15–25/month surcharge for 24 months. total cost: £500–800 vs £1,080 (£45 × 24). you're paying almost double for the privilege of instalments.
</p>
